issue.title: [Bug]: Path Traversal with Removed Nodes in ConditionalExpression
issue.body:
### 💻

- [ ] Would you like to work on a fix?

### How are you using Babel?

Programmatic API (`babel.transform`, `babel.parse`)

### Input code

It's a custom transform so it's hard to give an exact replication without working too hard on it, but here's the gist:

```js
console.log(a ? a() : b());
```

Where there is a custom transform plugin running over this source, which will inline the "DCE" branch if a is true to output:

```js
console.log(a());
```

Internally this is done via a check and replacement on the test node:

```js
if (t.isConditionalExpression(path.parentPath) && path.parentPath.node.consequent === path.node) {
  path.stop();
  path.parentPath.replaceWith(path.parentPath.get('consequent'));
}
```

In the above, it is still continuing to iterate the `b()` function. In addition, adding a `path.parentPath.get('alternate').remove()` results in the error:

```
     TypeError: unknown file: Property consequent of ConditionalExpression expected node to be of a type 
["Expression"] but instead got undefined
```

I understand this is a very specific iteration replacement case, but thought it worth posting anyway so at least there is some record of it.

### Configuration file name

_No response_

### Configuration

_No response_

### Current and expected behavior

It should be possible to remove a sibling Node and affect its iteration in a transform.

### Environment

7.20.5

### Possible solution

A liveness check in the iterator for replacements / removals / stop calls should properly be able to avoid iterating dead branches of the tree.

### Additional context

_No response_

issue.title: [Bug]: Duplicate declaration for type and value in ts
issue.body:
### 💻

- [ ] Would you like to work on a fix?

### How are you using Babel?

@babel/cli

### Input code

```ts
import { type Foo } from './foo'

function Foo() {}
```
[REPL](https://babeljs.io/repl#?browsers=&build=&builtIns=false&corejs=false&spec=false&loose=false&code_lz=JYWwDg9gTgLgBAbzjAnmApnAYhCcC-cAZlBCHAOQB0A9EbhQFCNECuAdgMYzATva4AFAEpE-RkA&debug=false&forceAllTransforms=false&shippedProposals=false&circleciRepo=&evaluate=false&fileSize=false&timeTravel=false&sourceType=module&lineWrap=false&presets=typescript&prettier=false&targets=&version=7.20.6&externalPlugins=&assumptions=%7B%7D)

### Configuration file name

babel.config.json

### Configuration

  "presets": [
    [
      "@babel/preset-env",
      {
        "targets": {
          "browsers": ["last 2 versions", "ie 11"]
        },
        "modules": "auto"
      }
    ],
    "@babel/preset-react",
    "@babel/preset-typescript"
  ],
  "plugins": ["@babel/plugin-proposal-class-properties"],
}

### Current and expected behavior

#### Current behavior

Babel throws an error : 
```
Duplicate declaration "Foo"
  1 | import { type Foo } from './foo'
  2 |
> 3 | function Foo() {}
    |          ^^^
  4 |
```

However there is no error if the type `Foo` is declared in the same file as the function `Foo`.

#### Expected behavior

Babel should accept that an imported type and a value can share the same name.

### Environment

Babel version: v7.20.5
Node: 16.15.1
Yarn: 1.22.19
OS: Linux 6.0 Arch Linux
Monorepo: yes (yarn workspaces)

### Possible solution

_No response_

issue.title: [Bug]: Error in `toString` during dynamic import should result in rejected promise
issue.body:
### 💻

- [ ] Would you like to work on a fix?

### How are you using Babel?

Other (Next.js, Gatsby, vue-cli, ...)

### Input code

```js
var filename = {
  toString: () => { throw "toString failure"; }
}

import(filename)
.then(obj => {
  console.log("import success");
})
.catch(err => {
  console.log("import failed");
});
```

### Configuration file name

_No response_

### Configuration

_No response_

### Current and expected behavior

[REPL](https://babeljs.io/repl/#?browsers=&build=&builtIns=false&corejs=3.21&spec=false&loose=false&code_lz=G4QwTgBAZglgNgUwHYgLYIgXggbwFAQQAuA9gMpFgxIDmAXBABQCUWAfLsQBZgkDuEAESkKVWtBDwArmASCA3BAC-eFXhioADiTBFGsRCnTM8AOiJdkjEgCMAVu1wEIAYxJIAziUSm4JGoyCGtq6EB5SLi4IHh6CzPKqJqYuIEQuXIwIYJCYHPiEbp7eCL7-gcE6RBLwCAAmcQlK8UA&debug=false&forceAllTransforms=false&shippedProposals=false&circleciRepo=&evaluate=false&fileSize=false&timeTravel=false&sourceType=script&lineWrap=true&presets=env&prettier=true&targets=&version=7.20.6&externalPlugins=&assumptions=%7B%7D)

The code above is transpiled into
```js
...
Promise.resolve("".concat(filename))
...
```
which results in throwing "toString failure".

However, since the exception is thrown during `toString`, the original import expression should result in [rejected promise](https://262.ecma-international.org/13.0/#sec-import-call-runtime-semantics-evaluation), and "import failed" should be printed.

### Environment

Tried at REPL (7.20.6)

### Possible solution

issue.title: [Bug]: RegExpStringIterator spreading throws Invalid attempt to spread non-iterable instance
issue.body:
### 💻

- [ ] Would you like to work on a fix?

### How are you using Babel?

babel-loader (webpack)

### Input code

```js
[...'foo.bar'.matchAll(/([^.[\]]+)/g)]
```


### Configuration file name

babel.config.js

### Configuration

```js
{
	presets: [
		'@babel/preset-env',
		'@babel/preset-react',
	],
}
```

### Current and expected behavior

Hello, 

trying to spread a `matchAll` result throws a `TypeError: Invalid attempt to spread non-iterable instance` exception.

It seems to be linked to this method `export default function _createForOfIteratorHelper(o, allowArrayLike)` which fails to identify a `RegExpStringIterator` as an iterator.

### Environment

Binaries:
    Node: 17.9.0 - /usr/bin/node
    npm: 8.5.5 - /usr/bin/npm

npmPackages:
    @babel/core: ^7.20.5 => 7.20.5 
    @babel/eslint-parser: ^7.19.1 => 7.19.1 
    @babel/preset-env: ^7.20.2 => 7.20.2

I was not able to reproduce it in repl so my guess is that I use an outdated version of babel, but I couldn't find the culprit

issue.title: Update module expressions parsing

labels.name: PR: Spec Compliance :eyeglasses:
labels.description: A type of pull request used for our changelog categories

issue.body: | Q                       | A | ------------------------ | --- | Fixed Issues? | Update module expression parsing to the current [Module expressions proposal](https://tc39.es/proposal-module-expressions/) | Patch: Bug Fix? | | Major: Breaking Change? | | Minor: New Feature? | | Tests Added + Pass? | Yes | Documentation PR Link | | Any Dependency Changes? | | License | MIT This PR can be reviewed by commits. First we enforce strict mode within the module body, then we disable `module {` at the start of the expression statement. The `export default ModuleExpression` production is also disabled. I suggest we parse it into a `ModuleDeclaration` node later (within the `moduleBlocks` plugin), otherwise we would generate different AST structures once the `ModuleDeclaration` proposal parsing is implemented and enabled.

issue.title: fix: Computed properties should keep original definition order
issue.body: | Q                       | A | ------------------------ | --- | Fixed Issues? | Fixes #15140 | Patch: Bug Fix? | :+1: | Major: Breaking Change? | | Minor: New Feature? | | Tests Added + Pass? | Yes | Documentation PR Link | | Any Dependency Changes? | | License | MIT `@babel/plugin-transform-computed-properties` use an `_mutatorMap` to hold the accessor computed properties in an object initializer, and use `defineEnumerableProperties` to define them at the end of initialization, which can change the definition order. This PR change it to use new helper function `defineAccessor` to define accessor computed properties in place, keeping the original definition order. #### Tests ##### :heavy_plus_sign: Added - babel-plugin-transform-computed-properties/test/fixtures/assumption-setComputedProperties/single-accessor - babel-plugin-transform-computed-properties/test/fixtures/regression/15140 - babel-plugin-transform-computed-properties/test/fixtures/spec/single-accessor ##### :wavy_dash: Output Changed - babel-plugin-transform-computed-properties/test/fixtures/assumption-setComputedProperties/accessors - babel-plugin-transform-computed-properties/test/fixtures/assumption-setComputedProperties/symbol - babel-plugin-transform-computed-properties/test/fixtures/spec/accessors - babel-plugin-transform-computed-properties/test/fixtures/spec/symbol

issue.title: Parse `using[foo]` as computed member expression

labels.name: PR: Bug Fix :bug:
labels.description: A type of pull request used for our changelog categories

issue.body: | Q                       | A | ------------------------ | --- | Fixed Issues? | Fixes #15221 | Patch: Bug Fix? | Yes | Major: Breaking Change? | | Minor: New Feature? | | Tests Added + Pass? | Yes | Documentation PR Link | | Any Dependency Changes? | | License | MIT This PR fixes a regression introduced in https://github.com/babel/babel/pull/14968. The `using` declaration forbids binding pattern. Previously we tried to recover from `using [`. However, unlike `let [`, `using [foo]` is already a valid expression statement (computed member expression). In this PR we only check if a name token is following `using`. I suggest reviewing this PR by commits. First we refactor the interface of `parseStatement` and `parseFunction`, then we create a separate branch for the `using` handling. The `hasFollowingIdentifier` method is now split into `hasFollowingBindingAtom` (for `let`) and `hasFollowingBindingIdentifier` (for `using`) so that we can implement the check without extra lookahead.

issue.title: Fix TaggedTemplate evaluation bug
issue.body: This line of code causes a type error since `TaggedTemplateLiteral`s do not have a property called "expressions". This change does what is probably expected. However, to maintain the existing behaviour, the line should instead be: ```js const exprs: Array> = path.isTemplateLiteral() ? path.get('expressions') : [] ```

issue.title: fix: Deleting super property should throw
issue.body: | Q                       | A | ------------------------ | --- | Fixed Issues? | Fixes #15169 | Patch: Bug Fix? | :+1: | Major: Breaking Change? | | Minor: New Feature? | | Tests Added + Pass? | Yes | Documentation PR Link | | Any Dependency Changes? | :+1: | License | MIT #### Spec Compliance `delete super.prop` and `delete super[expr]` should throw `ReferenceError`. Now they are transformed into: ```js // `delete super.prop` => function () { throw new ReferenceError("'delete super.prop' is invalid"); }() ``` ```js // `delete super[expr]` => ( babelHelpers.toPropertyKey(expr), function () { throw new ReferenceError("'delete super[expr]' is invalid"); }() ) ``` Thanks @Jack-Works and @nicolo-ribaudo for providing the correct transform. #### Tests - babel-plugin-transform-classes/test/fixtures/regression/15169 - babel-plugin-transform-classes/test/fixtures/spec/delete-super-property - babel-plugin-transform-classes/test/fixtures/spec/delete-super-property-to-property-key

issue.title: Implement await.ops transform

labels.name: PR: New Feature :rocket:
labels.description: A type of pull request used for our changelog categories

issue.body: | Q                       | A | ------------------------ | --- | Fixed Issues? | Support [Await Operations](https://github.com/tc39/proposal-await.ops/) | Patch: Bug Fix? | | Major: Breaking Change? | | Minor: New Feature? | Yes | Tests Added + Pass? | Yes | Documentation PR Link | | Any Dependency Changes? | | License | MIT This PR implements support of stage-1 Await Operations proposal. The plugin transforms `await.ops iterable` to `await Promise.ops(iterable)` where `ops` is one of `all|allSettled|any|race`. It assumes that the `Promise` variable is not shadowed or modified. The await.ops transform is copied to `babel-helper-remap-async-to-generator` because the async-await transform visits await expression prior to the await.ops transform. I didn't introduce a new helper package since 1) the transform is short and straightforward and 2) it is used by the plugin and async transform only.

issue.title: Add support to enable config caching in transform API
issue.body:
### 💻

- [ ] Would you like to work on this feature?

### What problem are you trying to solve?

I'm currently profiling the build pipeline of a bigger project and noticed that babel always reads the full config for every file it's transpiling. For this particular project that amounts to about **4s** overhead total. The config is static with the exception of the `filename` property.

If one opts to use a config file there is `api.cache`, but that's not accessible when calling `babel.transform()` directly.

### Describe the solution you'd like

A way to tell babel to reuse an existing config object instead of reloading it all the time. Not sure what the best way to do it would be. Maybe a referential equality check?

### Describe alternatives you've considered

Not sure

### Documentation, Adoption, Migration Strategy

_No response_

}
```

Both objects should include `"samsung": "13.0"`.

### Environment

No environment; this is an issue with `@babel/compat-data` on the `main` branch.

### Possible solution

It looks like this data is automatically generated based on `@mdn/browser-compat-data`. The version of `@mdn/browser-compat-data` in use is outdated; according to `yarn.lock`, it's `4.0.10`, which was published approximately one year ago (Nov 9, 2021).

Updating to the latest `@mdn/browser-compat-data` (which may involve breaking changes, given that it's on `5.2.16` now) should fix the issue, as well as any possible similar issues lurking in the dataset.

Having a mechanism in place to update the compatibility data dependency more frequently would be ideal.

### Additional context

_No response_

issue.title: [Bug]: Babel considering project config file when --config-file is active
issue.body:
### 💻

- [ ] Would you like to work on a fix?

### How are you using Babel?

@babel/cli

### Input code

```
Please see main description
```

### Configuration file name

babel.config.json

### Configuration

_No response_

### Current and expected behavior

I have the following project structure:

```
.
└── my-project/
    ├── .babelrc.json
    ├── package.json
    ├── src/
    │   ├── .babelrc.custom.json
    │   └── file.js
    └── dist/
        └── file.compiled.js
```

`.babelrc.json` has the following contents:
```
{
    "presets": [
        [
            "@babel/preset-env", {
                "debug": true,
            }
        ]
    ],
    "compact": false
  }
```

`.babelrc.custom.json` has the following content:
```
{
    "plugins": [
        "@babel/plugin-syntax-jsx"
    ],
    "sourceType": "module",
    "compact": false
}
```

I'm running Babel via a CLI command that looks like this:

```
npx babel ./src --config-file ./src/.babelrc.custom.json --out-dir ./dist
```

This CLI command is defined inside the package.json like this:

```
...
"scripts": {
    "build": "<cli-command-here>",
}
...
```

The issue I'm having is that `.babelrc.json` is interfering i.e. the code is being transpiled with `@babel/preset-env` instead of the single plugin defined in `.babelrc.custom.json`. Is this normal behavior, or a bug?

It's important to note that when I change the current working directory of the node process to `./src`, `.babelrc.json` no longer interferes.

My understanding is that when using `--config-file`, only the config file I define should apply. However, this is not the case. When I append `BABEL_SHOW_CONFIG_FOR=./src/file.js` to the command, it prints both configs, even though I specified only one i.e. `.babelrc.custom.json`.

Kindly advise.

### Environment

issue.title: build: improve artifacts IO
issue.body: | Q                       | A | ------------------------ | --- | Fixed Issues? | [It takes 1 min to download built artifacts for CI runners](https://github.com/babel/babel/actions/runs/3421423875/jobs/5697625889#step:7:1) | Patch: Bug Fix? | | Major: Breaking Change? | | Minor: New Feature? | | Tests Added + Pass? | Yes | Documentation PR Link | | Any Dependency Changes? | | License | MIT The artifact download is slow because [each file is uploaded separately to an HTTP endpoint](https://github.com/actions/upload-artifact#zipped-artifact-downloads). Currently there are 2355 files in the artifacts. In this PR we archive the artifacts before uploading, then we extract the archive after downloading. This approach is also [recommended by the `@actions/upload` maintainers](https://github.com/actions/upload-artifact#too-many-uploads-resulting-in-429-responses). After this PR, it takes less than 3 seconds to download and extract artifacts.

issue.body: | Q                       | A | ------------------------ | --- | Fixed Issues? | `Fixes #1, Fixes #2` | Patch: Bug Fix? | | Major: Breaking Change? | | Minor: New Feature? | | Tests Added + Pass? | Yes | Documentation PR Link | | Any Dependency Changes? | | License | MIT This PR changes our logic to check TDZ in AssignmentExpressions, so that we only generate code when the binding is possibly in TDZ. When compiling `let i; i = 0` the current main branch generates `var i; i; i = 0` (as shown by the first commit in this PR); after this PR we'll only generate `var i; i = 0`. I also refactored the code a bit to avoid some `@ts-expect-error`s caused by Node mutations, and I added a test for TDZ with UpdateExpressions which was completely untested. This PR doesn't fix any open issues, but I found the problem thanks to one of @p51lee's reports.

issue.title: [Bug]: Path Traversal with Removed Nodes in ConditionalExpression
issue.body:
### 💻

- [ ] Would you like to work on a fix?

### How are you using Babel?

Programmatic API (`babel.transform`, `babel.parse`)

### Input code

It's a custom transform so it's hard to give an exact replication without working too hard on it, but here's the gist:

```js
console.log(a ? a() : b());
```

Where there is a custom transform plugin running over this source, which will inline the "DCE" branch if a is true to output:

```js
console.log(a());
```

Internally this is done via a check and replacement on the test node:

```js
if (t.isConditionalExpression(path.parentPath) && path.parentPath.node.consequent === path.node) {
  path.stop();
  path.parentPath.replaceWith(path.parentPath.get('consequent'));
}
```

In the above, it is still continuing to iterate the `b()` function. In addition, adding a `path.parentPath.get('alternate').remove()` results in the error:

```
     TypeError: unknown file: Property consequent of ConditionalExpression expected node to be of a type 
["Expression"] but instead got undefined
```

I understand this is a very specific iteration replacement case, but thought it worth posting anyway so at least there is some record of it.

### Configuration file name

_No response_

### Configuration

_No response_

### Current and expected behavior

It should be possible to remove a sibling Node and affect its iteration in a transform.

### Environment

7.20.5

### Possible solution

A liveness check in the iterator for replacements / removals / stop calls should properly be able to avoid iterating dead branches of the tree.

### Additional context

_No response_

issue.title: [Bug]: Error in `toString` during dynamic import should result in rejected promise
issue.body:
### 💻

- [ ] Would you like to work on a fix?

### How are you using Babel?

Other (Next.js, Gatsby, vue-cli, ...)

### Input code

```js
var filename = {
  toString: () => { throw "toString failure"; }
}

import(filename)
.then(obj => {
  console.log("import success");
})
.catch(err => {
  console.log("import failed");
});
```

### Configuration file name

_No response_

### Configuration

_No response_

### Current and expected behavior

[REPL](https://babeljs.io/repl/#?browsers=&build=&builtIns=false&corejs=3.21&spec=false&loose=false&code_lz=G4QwTgBAZglgNgUwHYgLYIgXggbwFAQQAuA9gMpFgxIDmAXBABQCUWAfLsQBZgkDuEAESkKVWtBDwArmASCA3BAC-eFXhioADiTBFGsRCnTM8AOiJdkjEgCMAVu1wEIAYxJIAziUSm4JGoyCGtq6EB5SLi4IHh6CzPKqJqYuIEQuXIwIYJCYHPiEbp7eCL7-gcE6RBLwCAAmcQlK8UA&debug=false&forceAllTransforms=false&shippedProposals=false&circleciRepo=&evaluate=false&fileSize=false&timeTravel=false&sourceType=script&lineWrap=true&presets=env&prettier=true&targets=&version=7.20.6&externalPlugins=&assumptions=%7B%7D)

The code above is transpiled into
```js
...
Promise.resolve("".concat(filename))
...
```
which results in throwing "toString failure".

However, since the exception is thrown during `toString`, the original import expression should result in [rejected promise](https://262.ecma-international.org/13.0/#sec-import-call-runtime-semantics-evaluation), and "import failed" should be printed.

labels.name: PR: Spec Compliance :eyeglasses:
labels.description: A type of pull request used for our changelog categories

issue.body: | Q                       | A | ------------------------ | --- | Fixed Issues? | Update module expression parsing to the current [Module expressions proposal](https://tc39.es/proposal-module-expressions/) | Patch: Bug Fix? | | Major: Breaking Change? | | Minor: New Feature? | | Tests Added + Pass? | Yes | Documentation PR Link | | Any Dependency Changes? | | License | MIT This PR can be reviewed by commits. First we enforce strict mode within the module body, then we disable `module {` at the start of the expression statement. The `export default ModuleExpression` production is also disabled. I suggest we parse it into a `ModuleDeclaration` node later (within the `moduleBlocks` plugin), otherwise we would generate different AST structures once the `ModuleDeclaration` proposal parsing is implemented and enabled.

issue.title: fix: Computed properties should keep original definition order
issue.body: | Q                       | A | ------------------------ | --- | Fixed Issues? | Fixes #15140 | Patch: Bug Fix? | :+1: | Major: Breaking Change? | | Minor: New Feature? | | Tests Added + Pass? | Yes | Documentation PR Link | | Any Dependency Changes? | | License | MIT `@babel/plugin-transform-computed-properties` use an `_mutatorMap` to hold the accessor computed properties in an object initializer, and use `defineEnumerableProperties` to define them at the end of initialization, which can change the definition order. issue.title: Parse `using[foo]` as computed member expression

labels.name: PR: Bug Fix :bug:
labels.description: A type of pull request used for our changelog categories

issue.body: | Q                       | A | ------------------------ | --- | Fixed Issues? | Fixes #15221 | Patch: Bug Fix? | Yes | Major: Breaking Change? | | Minor: New Feature? | | Tests Added + Pass? | Yes | Documentation PR Link | | Any Dependency Changes? | | License | MIT This PR fixes a regression introduced in https://github.com/babel/babel/pull/14968. The `using` declaration forbids binding pattern. Previously we tried to recover from `using [`. However, unlike `let [`, `using [foo]` is already a valid expression statement (computed member expression). In this PR we only check if a name token is following `using`. I suggest reviewing this PR by commits. First we refactor the interface of `parseStatement` and `parseFunction`, then we create a separate branch for the `using` handling. The `hasFollowingIdentifier` method is now split into `hasFollowingBindingAtom` (for `let`) and `hasFollowingBindingIdentifier` (for `using`) so that we can implement the check without extra lookahead.

https://github.com/babel/babel/blob/e7405b99695b4b499a7a9494e4b5ecb1adc2e445/packages/babel-parser/test/fixtures/experimental/explicit-resource-management/invalid-using-binding-pattern/input.js#L3

but the behaviour is not correct since it is already valid JS.

issue.title: Implement await.ops transform

labels.name: PR: New Feature :rocket:
labels.description: A type of pull request used for our changelog categories

issue.body: | Q                       | A | ------------------------ | --- | Fixed Issues? | Support [Await Operations](https://github.com/tc39/proposal-await.ops/) | Patch: Bug Fix? | | Major: Breaking Change? | | Minor: New Feature? | Yes | Tests Added + Pass? | Yes | Documentation PR Link | | Any Dependency Changes? | | License | MIT This PR implements support of stage-1 Await Operations proposal. The plugin transforms `await.ops iterable` to `await Promise.ops(iterable)` where `ops` is one of `all|allSettled|any|race`. It assumes that the `Promise` variable is not shadowed or modified. The await.ops transform is copied to `babel-helper-remap-async-to-generator` because the async-await transform visits await expression prior to the await.ops transform. I didn't introduce a new helper package since 1) the transform is short and straightforward and 2) it is used by the plugin and async transform only.

issue.title: Add support to enable config caching in transform API
issue.body:
### 💻

- [ ] Would you like to work on this feature?

### What problem are you trying to solve?

I'm currently profiling the build pipeline of a bigger project and noticed that babel always reads the full config for every file it's transpiling. For this particular project that amounts to about **4s** overhead total. The config is static with the exception of the `filename` property.

If one opts to use a config file there is `api.cache`, but that's not accessible when calling `babel.transform()` directly.

### Describe the solution you'd like

A way to tell babel to reuse an existing config object instead of reloading it all the time. Not sure what the best way to do it would be. Maybe a referential equality check?

### Describe alternatives you've considered

Not sure

### Documentation, Adoption, Migration Strategy

_No response_

issue.title: [Bug]: Missing compat data information for optional chaining on Samsung Internet
issue.body:
### 💻

- [ ] Would you like to work on a fix?

### How are you using Babel?

Other (Next.js, Gatsby, vue-cli, ...)

### Input code

No input code; this is an issue with `@babel/compat-data`.

### Configuration file name

_No response_

### Configuration

_No response_

### Current and expected behavior

`@babel/compat-data` is missing support information for optional chaining on Samsung Internet. As per [`plugins.json`](https://github.com/babel/babel/blob/main/packages/babel-compat-data/data/plugins.json):

```  
"transform-optional-chaining": {
  "chrome": "91",
  "opera": "77",
  "edge": "91",
  "firefox": "74",
  "safari": "13.1",
  "node": "16.9",
  "deno": "1.9",
  "ios": "13.4",
  "electron": "13.0"
},
"proposal-optional-chaining": {
  "chrome": "91",
  "opera": "77",
  "edge": "91",
  "firefox": "74",
  "safari": "13.1",
  "node": "16.9",
  "deno": "1.9",
  "ios": "13.4",
  "electron": "13.0"
}
```

Both objects should include `"samsung": "13.0"`.

### Environment

No environment; this is an issue with `@babel/compat-data` on the `main` branch.

### Possible solution

It looks like this data is automatically generated based on `@mdn/browser-compat-data`. The version of `@mdn/browser-compat-data` in use is outdated; according to `yarn.lock`, it's `4.0.10`, which was published approximately one year ago (Nov 9, 2021).

Updating to the latest `@mdn/browser-compat-data` (which may involve breaking changes, given that it's on `5.2.16` now) should fix the issue, as well as any possible similar issues lurking in the dataset.

Having a mechanism in place to update the compatibility data dependency more frequently would be ideal.

### Additional context

_No response_

issue.body:
### 💻

### How are you using Babel?

babel-loader (webpack)

### Input code

https://babel.dev/repl#?browsers=defaults%2C%20not%20ie%2011%2C%20not%20ie_mob%2011&build=&builtIns=false&corejs=3.21&spec=false&loose=false&code_lz=PTAEHcHsCcGsGcBQBLAtgBxgF1KyATAVwBsBTUAM2klVAHI8iy6BuRECGBFDbUAb1ABjaKQCGWUgCVSAR0LJRoAL6VqtBgRKlW7MACNRY7mkzQcjbQBoBwo5JnzF5VVRr1LzFkA&debug=false&forceAllTransforms=false&shippedProposals=false&circleciRepo=&evaluate=false&fileSize=false&timeTravel=false&sourceType=module&lineWrap=true&presets=&prettier=false&targets=&version=7.20.4&externalPlugins=&assumptions=%7B%7D

### Configuration file name

_No response_

### Configuration

_No response_

### Current and expected behavior

In our monorepo, one of the packages has a line like:

`import module, { createRequire } from 'module';`

for the actual [node Module API](https://nodejs.org/api/module.html). On a recent upgrade attempt (@babel/parser 7.19.4 -> 7.20.1 I believe), we were seeing `Support for the experimental syntax 'importReflection' isn't currently enabled`, however, this is not an attempted usage of importReflection. I suspect the logic [introduced in this PR](https://github.com/babel/babel/pull/14926/files#diff-dde20a4c39ac9fc963a227ec21025e1af1368f92d8c0d1db85274b199adb1cf4R2666) incorrectly flags this case as importReflection.

Workaround was to simply change the default import name.

Expected behavior would be for `module` to work as a default import name when also importing named functions, regardless of `importReflection` status.

issue.title: [Bug]: Babel considering project config file when --config-file is active
issue.body:
### 💻

- [ ] Would you like to work on a fix?

### How are you using Babel?

@babel/cli

### Input code

```
Please see main description
```

### Configuration file name

babel.config.json

### Configuration

_No response_

### Current and expected behavior

I have the following project structure:

```
.
└── my-project/
    ├── .babelrc.json
    ├── package.json
    ├── src/
    │   ├── .babelrc.custom.json
    │   └── file.js
    └── dist/
        └── file.compiled.js
```

`.babelrc.json` has the following contents:
```
{
    "presets": [
        [
            "@babel/preset-env", {
                "debug": true,
            }
        ]
    ],
    "compact": false
  }
```

`.babelrc.custom.json` has the following content:
```
{
    "plugins": [
        "@babel/plugin-syntax-jsx"
    ],
    "sourceType": "module",
    "compact": false
}
```

I'm running Babel via a CLI command that looks like this:

```
npx babel ./src --config-file ./src/.babelrc.custom.json --out-dir ./dist
```

This CLI command is defined inside the package.json like this:

```
...
"scripts": {
    "build": "<cli-command-here>",
}
...
```

The issue I'm having is that `.babelrc.json` is interfering i.e. the code is being transpiled with `@babel/preset-env` instead of the single plugin defined in `.babelrc.custom.json`. Is this normal behavior, or a bug?

It's important to note that when I change the current working directory of the node process to `./src`, `.babelrc.json` no longer interferes.

My understanding is that when using `--config-file`, only the config file I define should apply. However, this is not the case. When I append `BABEL_SHOW_CONFIG_FOR=./src/file.js` to the command, it prints both configs, even though I specified only one i.e. `.babelrc.custom.json`.

Kindly advise.

### Environment

System:
    OS: macOS High Sierra 10.13.6

    Node: 16.15.0 - /usr/local/bin/node
    Yarn: 1.22.18 - /usr/local/bin/yarn

    eslint: ^8.27.0 => 8.27.0 
    jest: ^29.3.1 => 29.3.1 

### Possible solution

If this is normal behavior, it would be important to note this in the official docs.

issue.title: [Bug]: Wrong TDZ logic (switch-case and class in function)
issue.body:
### 💻

- [ ] Would you like to work on a fix?

### How are you using Babel?

@babel/cli

### Input code

```js
// case 1
switch ( 0 ) { default : let x ; case x : } 
// case 2
( x => y ) ( ) ; class y {};
```

### Configuration file name

_No response_

### Configuration

```json
{
  "presets": [
    "@babel/preset-env"
  ],
  "plugins": [
    [
      "@babel/plugin-transform-block-scoping",
      {
        "tdz": true
      }
    ]
  ]
}
```

### Current and expected behavior

Both case 1 and 2 should throw `ReferenceError` but they are terminated normally:
```console
$ npx babel input1.js | node # no error
$ npx babel input2.js | node # no error
```
```console
$ node input1.js
input1.js:1
switch ( 0 ) { default : let x ; case x : }
                                      ^

ReferenceError: Cannot access 'x' before initialization
...
Node.js v18.11.0

$ node input2.js
input2.js:1
( x => y ) ( ) ; class y {};
       ^

ReferenceError: Cannot access 'y' before initialization
...
Node.js v18.11.0
```

### Environment

npm version 8.19.2

@babel/cli@7.19.3
@babel/core@7.20.2
@babel/plugin-transform-block-scoping@7.20.2
@babel/preset-env@7.20.2

node version 18.11.0
macos version 13.0

_No response_

issue.title: [Bug]: Order between TDZ errors and other errors
issue.body:
### 💻

- [ ] Would you like to work on a fix?

### How are you using Babel?

@babel/cli

### Input code

```js
let x = { x = 0 ( ) } = 0 ; 
```

### Configuration file name

.babelrc

### Configuration

```json
{
  "plugins": [
    [
      "@babel/plugin-transform-block-scoping",
      {
        "tdz": true
      }
    ]
  ]
}
```

### Current and expected behavior

Input code is expected to throw `TypeError`:
```console
$ node input.js
input.js:1
let x = { x = 0 ( ) } = 0 ;
                ^

TypeError: 0 is not a function
    at Object.<anonymous> (input.js:1:17)
    at Module._compile (node:internal/modules/cjs/loader:1159:14)
    at Module._extensions..js (node:internal/modules/cjs/loader:1213:10)
    at Module.load (node:internal/modules/cjs/loader:1037:32)
    at Module._load (node:internal/modules/cjs/loader:878:12)
    at Function.executeUserEntryPoint [as runMain] (node:internal/modules/run_main:81:12)
    at node:internal/main/run_main_module:23:47

Node.js v18.11.0
```
but output code is transpiled as following:
```js
function _tdz(name) { throw new ReferenceError(name + " is not defined - temporal dead zone"); }
var x = (_tdz("x"), ({
  x = 0()
} = 0));
```
and is throwing `ReferenceError` due to `_tdz` function:

```console
$ npx babel input.js | node
[stdin]:1
function _tdz(name) { throw new ReferenceError(name + " is not defined - temporal dead zone"); }
                      ^

ReferenceError: x is not defined - temporal dead zone
    at _tdz ([stdin]:1:29)
    at [stdin]:2:10
    at Script.runInThisContext (node:vm:129:12)
    at Object.runInThisContext (node:vm:313:38)
    at node:internal/process/execution:79:19
    at [stdin]-wrapper:6:22
    at evalScript (node:internal/process/execution:78:60)
    at node:internal/main/eval_stdin:30:5
    at Socket.<anonymous> (node:internal/process/execution:195:5)
    at Socket.emit (node:events:525:35)

Node.js v18.11.0
```

### Environment

Babel version: 7.20.2
Node: v18.11.0
npm version: 8.19.2
OS: macos 13.0

### Possible solution

_No response_

### Additional context

_No response_

issue.title: build: improve artifacts IO
issue.body: | Q                       | A | ------------------------ | --- | Fixed Issues? | [It takes 1 min to download built artifacts for CI runners](https://github.com/babel/babel/actions/runs/3421423875/jobs/5697625889#step:7:1) | Patch: Bug Fix? | | Major: Breaking Change? | | Minor: New Feature? | | Tests Added + Pass? | Yes | Documentation PR Link | | Any Dependency Changes? | | License | MIT The artifact download is slow because [each file is uploaded separately to an HTTP endpoint](https://github.com/actions/upload-artifact#zipped-artifact-downloads). Currently there are 2355 files in the artifacts. In this PR we archive the artifacts before uploading, then we extract the archive after downloading. This approach is also [recommended by the `@actions/upload` maintainers](https://github.com/actions/upload-artifact#too-many-uploads-resulting-in-429-responses). After this PR, it takes less than 3 seconds to download and extract artifacts.

issue.title: Only extract IDs for TDZ checks in assign when necessary

labels.name: PR: Polish :nail_care:
labels.description: A type of pull request used for our changelog categories

issue.body: | Q                       | A | ------------------------ | --- | Fixed Issues? | `Fixes #1, Fixes #2` | Patch: Bug Fix? | | Major: Breaking Change? | | Minor: New Feature? | | Tests Added + Pass? | Yes | Documentation PR Link | | Any Dependency Changes? | | License | MIT This PR changes our logic to check TDZ in AssignmentExpressions, so that we only generate code when the binding is possibly in TDZ. When compiling `let i; i = 0` the current main branch generates `var i; i; i = 0` (as shown by the first commit in this PR); after this PR we'll only generate `var i; i = 0`. I also refactored the code a bit to avoid some `@ts-expect-error`s caused by Node mutations, and I added a test for TDZ with UpdateExpressions which was completely untested. This PR doesn't fix any open issues, but I found the problem thanks to one of @p51lee's reports.

issue.title: [Bug]: Path Traversal with Removed Nodes in ConditionalExpression
issue.body:
### 💻

- [ ] Would you like to work on a fix?

### How are you using Babel?

Programmatic API (`babel.transform`, `babel.parse`)

### Input code

It's a custom transform so it's hard to give an exact replication without working too hard on it, but here's the gist:

```js
console.log(a ? a() : b());
```

Where there is a custom transform plugin running over this source, which will inline the "DCE" branch if a is true to output:

```js
console.log(a());
```

Internally this is done via a check and replacement on the test node:

```js
if (t.isConditionalExpression(path.parentPath) && path.parentPath.node.consequent === path.node) {
  path.stop();
  path.parentPath.replaceWith(path.parentPath.get('consequent'));
}
```

In the above, it is still continuing to iterate the `b()` function. In addition, adding a `path.parentPath.get('alternate').remove()` results in the error:

```
     TypeError: unknown file: Property consequent of ConditionalExpression expected node to be of a type 
["Expression"] but instead got undefined
```

I understand this is a very specific iteration replacement case, but thought it worth posting anyway so at least there is some record of it.

### Configuration file name

_No response_

### Configuration

_No response_

### Current and expected behavior

It should be possible to remove a sibling Node and affect its iteration in a transform.

### Environment

7.20.5

### Possible solution

A liveness check in the iterator for replacements / removals / stop calls should properly be able to avoid iterating dead branches of the tree.

### Additional context

_No response_

issue.title: [Bug]: Error in `toString` during dynamic import should result in rejected promise
issue.body:
### 💻

- [ ] Would you like to work on a fix?

### How are you using Babel?

Other (Next.js, Gatsby, vue-cli, ...)

### Input code

```js
var filename = {
  toString: () => { throw "toString failure"; }
}

import(filename)
.then(obj => {
  console.log("import success");
})
.catch(err => {
  console.log("import failed");
});
```

### Configuration file name

_No response_

### Configuration

_No response_

### Current and expected behavior

[REPL](https://babeljs.io/repl/#?browsers=&build=&builtIns=false&corejs=3.21&spec=false&loose=false&code_lz=G4QwTgBAZglgNgUwHYgLYIgXggbwFAQQAuA9gMpFgxIDmAXBABQCUWAfLsQBZgkDuEAESkKVWtBDwArmASCA3BAC-eFXhioADiTBFGsRCnTM8AOiJdkjEgCMAVu1wEIAYxJIAziUSm4JGoyCGtq6EB5SLi4IHh6CzPKqJqYuIEQuXIwIYJCYHPiEbp7eCL7-gcE6RBLwCAAmcQlK8UA&debug=false&forceAllTransforms=false&shippedProposals=false&circleciRepo=&evaluate=false&fileSize=false&timeTravel=false&sourceType=script&lineWrap=true&presets=env&prettier=true&targets=&version=7.20.6&externalPlugins=&assumptions=%7B%7D)

The code above is transpiled into
```js
...
Promise.resolve("".concat(filename))
...
```
which results in throwing "toString failure".

However, since the exception is thrown during `toString`, the original import expression should result in [rejected promise](https://262.ecma-international.org/13.0/#sec-import-call-runtime-semantics-evaluation), and "import failed" should be printed.

### Environment

Tried at REPL (7.20.6)

babel-loader (webpack)

```js
[...'foo.bar'.matchAll(/([^.[\]]+)/g)]
```


### Configuration file name

babel.config.js

{
	presets: [

issue.title: Update module expressions parsing

labels.name: PR: Spec Compliance :eyeglasses:
labels.description: A type of pull request used for our changelog categories

issue.body: | Q                       | A | ------------------------ | --- | Fixed Issues? | Update module expression parsing to the current [Module expressions proposal](https://tc39.es/proposal-module-expressions/) | Patch: Bug Fix? | | Major: Breaking Change? | | Minor: New Feature? | | Tests Added + Pass? | Yes | Documentation PR Link | | Any Dependency Changes? | | License | MIT This PR can be reviewed by commits. First we enforce strict mode within the module body, then we disable `module {` at the start of the expression statement. The `export default ModuleExpression` production is also disabled. I suggest we parse it into a `ModuleDeclaration` node later (within the `moduleBlocks` plugin), otherwise we would generate different AST structures once the `ModuleDeclaration` proposal parsing is implemented and enabled.

issue.title: fix: Computed properties should keep original definition order
issue.body: | Q                       | A | ------------------------ | --- | Fixed Issues? | Fixes #15140 | Patch: Bug Fix? | :+1: | Major: Breaking Change? | | Minor: New Feature? | | Tests Added + Pass? | Yes | Documentation PR Link | | Any Dependency Changes? | | License | MIT `@babel/plugin-transform-computed-properties` use an `_mutatorMap` to hold the accessor computed properties in an object initializer, and use `defineEnumerableProperties` to define them at the end of initialization, which can change the definition order. This PR change it to use new helper function `defineAccessor` to define accessor computed properties in place, keeping the original definition order. #### Tests ##### :heavy_plus_sign: Added - babel-plugin-transform-computed-properties/test/fixtures/assumption-setComputedProperties/single-accessor - babel-plugin-transform-computed-properties/test/fixtures/regression/15140 - babel-plugin-transform-computed-properties/test/fixtures/spec/single-accessor ##### :wavy_dash: Output Changed - babel-plugin-transform-computed-properties/test/fixtures/assumption-setComputedProperties/accessors - babel-plugin-transform-computed-properties/test/fixtures/assumption-setComputedProperties/symbol - babel-plugin-transform-computed-properties/test/fixtures/spec/accessors - babel-plugin-transform-computed-properties/test/fixtures/spec/symbol

issue.title: Parse `using[foo]` as computed member expression

labels.name: PR: Bug Fix :bug:
labels.description: A type of pull request used for our changelog categories

issue.body: | Q                       | A | ------------------------ | --- | Fixed Issues? | Fixes #15221 | Patch: Bug Fix? | Yes | Major: Breaking Change? | | Minor: New Feature? | | Tests Added + Pass? | Yes | Documentation PR Link | | Any Dependency Changes? | | License | MIT This PR fixes a regression introduced in https://github.com/babel/babel/pull/14968. The `using` declaration forbids binding pattern. Previously we tried to recover from `using [`. However, unlike `let [`, `using [foo]` is already a valid expression statement (computed member expression). In this PR we only check if a name token is following `using`. I suggest reviewing this PR by commits. First we refactor the interface of `parseStatement` and `parseFunction`, then we create a separate branch for the `using` handling. The `hasFollowingIdentifier` method is now split into `hasFollowingBindingAtom` (for `let`) and `hasFollowingBindingIdentifier` (for `using`) so that we can implement the check without extra lookahead.

issue.title: fix: Deleting super property should throw
issue.body: | Q                       | A | ------------------------ | --- | Fixed Issues? | Fixes #15169 | Patch: Bug Fix? | :+1: | Major: Breaking Change? | | Minor: New Feature? | | Tests Added + Pass? | Yes | Documentation PR Link | | Any Dependency Changes? | :+1: | License | MIT #### Spec Compliance `delete super.prop` and `delete super[expr]` should throw `ReferenceError`. Now they are transformed into: ```js // `delete super.prop` => function () { throw new ReferenceError("'delete super.prop' is invalid"); }() ``` ```js // `delete super[expr]` => ( babelHelpers.toPropertyKey(expr), function () { throw new ReferenceError("'delete super[expr]' is invalid"); }() ) ``` Thanks @Jack-Works and @nicolo-ribaudo for providing the correct transform. #### Tests - babel-plugin-transform-classes/test/fixtures/regression/15169 - babel-plugin-transform-classes/test/fixtures/spec/delete-super-property - babel-plugin-transform-classes/test/fixtures/spec/delete-super-property-to-property-key

labels.name: PR: New Feature :rocket:
labels.description: A type of pull request used for our changelog categories

issue.body: | Q                       | A | ------------------------ | --- | Fixed Issues? | Support [Await Operations](https://github.com/tc39/proposal-await.ops/) | Patch: Bug Fix? | | Major: Breaking Change? | | Minor: New Feature? | Yes | Tests Added + Pass? | Yes | Documentation PR Link | | Any Dependency Changes? | | License | MIT This PR implements support of stage-1 Await Operations proposal. The plugin transforms `await.ops iterable` to `await Promise.ops(iterable)` where `ops` is one of `all|allSettled|any|race`. It assumes that the `Promise` variable is not shadowed or modified. The await.ops transform is copied to `babel-helper-remap-async-to-generator` because the async-await transform visits await expression prior to the await.ops transform. I didn't introduce a new helper package since 1) the transform is short and straightforward and 2) it is used by the plugin and async transform only.

issue.title: Add support to enable config caching in transform API
issue.body:
### 💻

- [ ] Would you like to work on this feature?

### What problem are you trying to solve?

I'm currently profiling the build pipeline of a bigger project and noticed that babel always reads the full config for every file it's transpiling. For this particular project that amounts to about **4s** overhead total. The config is static with the exception of the `filename` property.

If one opts to use a config file there is `api.cache`, but that's not accessible when calling `babel.transform()` directly.

### Describe the solution you'd like

A way to tell babel to reuse an existing config object instead of reloading it all the time. Not sure what the best way to do it would be. Maybe a referential equality check?

### Describe alternatives you've considered

Not sure

### Documentation, Adoption, Migration Strategy

_No response_

issue.title: [Bug]: Missing compat data information for optional chaining on Samsung Internet
issue.body:
### 💻

- [ ] Would you like to work on a fix?

### How are you using Babel?

Other (Next.js, Gatsby, vue-cli, ...)

### Input code

No input code; this is an issue with `@babel/compat-data`.

### Configuration file name

_No response_

### Configuration

_No response_

### Current and expected behavior

`@babel/compat-data` is missing support information for optional chaining on Samsung Internet. As per [`plugins.json`](https://github.com/babel/babel/blob/main/packages/babel-compat-data/data/plugins.json):

```  
"transform-optional-chaining": {
  "chrome": "91",
  "opera": "77",
  "edge": "91",
  "firefox": "74",
  "safari": "13.1",
  "node": "16.9",
  "deno": "1.9",
  "ios": "13.4",
  "electron": "13.0"
},
"proposal-optional-chaining": {
  "chrome": "91",
  "opera": "77",
  "edge": "91",
  "firefox": "74",
  "safari": "13.1",
  "node": "16.9",
  "deno": "1.9",
  "ios": "13.4",
  "electron": "13.0"
}
```

Both objects should include `"samsung": "13.0"`.

### Environment

No environment; this is an issue with `@babel/compat-data` on the `main` branch.

### Possible solution

It looks like this data is automatically generated based on `@mdn/browser-compat-data`. The version of `@mdn/browser-compat-data` in use is outdated; according to `yarn.lock`, it's `4.0.10`, which was published approximately one year ago (Nov 9, 2021).

Updating to the latest `@mdn/browser-compat-data` (which may involve breaking changes, given that it's on `5.2.16` now) should fix the issue, as well as any possible similar issues lurking in the dataset.

Having a mechanism in place to update the compatibility data dependency more frequently would be ideal.

### Additional context

_No response_

_No response_

_No response_

### Current and expected behavior

In our monorepo, one of the packages has a line like:

`import module, { createRequire } from 'module';`

for the actual [node Module API](https://nodejs.org/api/module.html). On a recent upgrade attempt (@babel/parser 7.19.4 -> 7.20.1 I believe), we were seeing `Support for the experimental syntax 'importReflection' isn't currently enabled`, however, this is not an attempted usage of importReflection. issue.body:
### 💻

- [ ] Would you like to work on a fix?

### How are you using Babel?

@babel/cli

### Input code

```
Please see main description
```

### Configuration file name

babel.config.json

### Configuration

_No response_

### Current and expected behavior

I have the following project structure:

```
.
└── my-project/
    ├── .babelrc.json
    ├── package.json
    ├── src/
    │   ├── .babelrc.custom.json
    │   └── file.js
    └── dist/
        └── file.compiled.js
```

`.babelrc.json` has the following contents:
```
{
    "presets": [
        [
            "@babel/preset-env", {
                "debug": true,
            }
        ]
    ],
    "compact": false
  }
```

`.babelrc.custom.json` has the following content:
```
{
    "plugins": [
        "@babel/plugin-syntax-jsx"
    ],
    "sourceType": "module",
    "compact": false
}
```

I'm running Babel via a CLI command that looks like this:

```
npx babel ./src --config-file ./src/.babelrc.custom.json --out-dir ./dist
```

This CLI command is defined inside the package.json like this:

```
...
"scripts": {
    "build": "<cli-command-here>",
}
...
```

The issue I'm having is that `.babelrc.json` is interfering i.e. the code is being transpiled with `@babel/preset-env` instead of the single plugin defined in `.babelrc.custom.json`. Is this normal behavior, or a bug?

It's important to note that when I change the current working directory of the node process to `./src`, `.babelrc.json` no longer interferes.

My understanding is that when using `--config-file`, only the config file I define should apply. However, this is not the case. When I append `BABEL_SHOW_CONFIG_FOR=./src/file.js` to the command, it prints both configs, even though I specified only one i.e. `.babelrc.custom.json`.

Kindly advise.

issue.title: [Bug]: Wrong TDZ logic (switch-case and class in function)
issue.body:
### 💻

- [ ] Would you like to work on a fix?

### How are you using Babel?

@babel/cli

### Input code

```js
// case 1
switch ( 0 ) { default : let x ; case x : } 
// case 2
( x => y ) ( ) ; class y {};
```

### Configuration file name

_No response_

### Configuration

```json
{
  "presets": [
    "@babel/preset-env"
  ],
  "plugins": [
    [
      "@babel/plugin-transform-block-scoping",
      {
        "tdz": true
      }
    ]
  ]
}
```

### Current and expected behavior

Both case 1 and 2 should throw `ReferenceError` but they are terminated normally:
```console
$ npx babel input1.js | node # no error
$ npx babel input2.js | node # no error
```
```console
$ node input1.js
input1.js:1
switch ( 0 ) { default : let x ; case x : }
                                      ^

ReferenceError: Cannot access 'x' before initialization
...
Node.js v18.11.0

$ node input2.js
input2.js:1
( x => y ) ( ) ; class y {};
       ^

ReferenceError: Cannot access 'y' before initialization
...
Node.js v18.11.0
```

### Environment

npm version 8.19.2

@babel/cli@7.19.3
@babel/core@7.20.2
@babel/plugin-transform-block-scoping@7.20.2
@babel/preset-env@7.20.2

node version 18.11.0
macos version 13.0

issue.title: [Bug]: Order between TDZ errors and other errors
issue.body:
### 💻

- [ ] Would you like to work on a fix?

### How are you using Babel?

@babel/cli

### Input code

```js
let x = { x = 0 ( ) } = 0 ; 
```

### Configuration file name

.babelrc

### Configuration

```json
{
  "plugins": [
    [
      "@babel/plugin-transform-block-scoping",
      {
        "tdz": true
      }
    ]
  ]
}
```

### Current and expected behavior

Input code is expected to throw `TypeError`:
```console
$ node input.js
input.js:1
let x = { x = 0 ( ) } = 0 ;
                ^

TypeError: 0 is not a function
    at Object.<anonymous> (input.js:1:17)
    at Module._compile (node:internal/modules/cjs/loader:1159:14)
    at Module._extensions..js (node:internal/modules/cjs/loader:1213:10)

    at Module._load (node:internal/modules/cjs/loader:878:12)
    at Function.executeUserEntryPoint [as runMain] (node:internal/modules/run_main:81:12)
    at node:internal/main/run_main_module:23:47

Node.js v18.11.0
```
but output code is transpiled as following:
```js
function _tdz(name) { throw new ReferenceError(name + " is not defined - temporal dead zone"); }
var x = (_tdz("x"), ({
  x = 0()
} = 0));
```
and is throwing `ReferenceError` due to `_tdz` function:

```console
$ npx babel input.js | node
[stdin]:1
function _tdz(name) { throw new ReferenceError(name + " is not defined - temporal dead zone"); }
                      ^

ReferenceError: x is not defined - temporal dead zone
    at _tdz ([stdin]:1:29)
    at [stdin]:2:10
    at Script.runInThisContext (node:vm:129:12)
    at Object.runInThisContext (node:vm:313:38)
    at node:internal/process/execution:79:19

    at evalScript (node:internal/process/execution:78:60)
    at node:internal/main/eval_stdin:30:5
    at Socket.<anonymous> (node:internal/process/execution:195:5)
    at Socket.emit (node:events:525:35)

Node.js v18.11.0
```

OS: macos 13.0

issue.title: build: improve artifacts IO
issue.body: | Q                       | A | ------------------------ | --- | Fixed Issues? | [It takes 1 min to download built artifacts for CI runners](https://github.com/babel/babel/actions/runs/3421423875/jobs/5697625889#step:7:1) | Patch: Bug Fix? | | Major: Breaking Change? | | Minor: New Feature? | | Tests Added + Pass? | Yes | Documentation PR Link | | Any Dependency Changes? | | License | MIT The artifact download is slow because [each file is uploaded separately to an HTTP endpoint](https://github.com/actions/upload-artifact#zipped-artifact-downloads). Currently there are 2355 files in the artifacts. In this PR we archive the artifacts before uploading, then we extract the archive after downloading. This approach is also [recommended by the `@actions/upload` maintainers](https://github.com/actions/upload-artifact#too-many-uploads-resulting-in-429-responses). After this PR, it takes less than 3 seconds to download and extract artifacts.

issue.title: Only extract IDs for TDZ checks in assign when necessary

labels.name: PR: Polish :nail_care:
labels.description: A type of pull request used for our changelog categories

issue.body: | Q                       | A | ------------------------ | --- | Fixed Issues? | `Fixes #1, Fixes #2` | Patch: Bug Fix? | | Major: Breaking Change? | | Minor: New Feature? | | Tests Added + Pass? | Yes | Documentation PR Link | | Any Dependency Changes? | | License | MIT This PR changes our logic to check TDZ in AssignmentExpressions, so that we only generate code when the binding is possibly in TDZ. When compiling `let i; i = 0` the current main branch generates `var i; i; i = 0` (as shown by the first commit in this PR); after this PR we'll only generate `var i; i = 0`. I also refactored the code a bit to avoid some `@ts-expect-error`s caused by Node mutations, and I added a test for TDZ with UpdateExpressions which was completely untested. This PR doesn't fix any open issues, but I found the problem thanks to one of @p51lee's reports.
